out_desc_tool: Post-test unadjusted mean score. The test was made up of two tasks involving (1) alliteration and (2)rhymes. Each included 10 two-syllable word pairs. On the alliteration task, children were asked if the first syllable of a word resembled or differed from the first syllable of its paired word. On the rhyming task, we asked the same question with reference to word pairs’ final syllables. The mean correct answers across the two-tasks served as the total phonological awareness score.

On the alliteration task, children were asked if the first syllable of a word resembled or differed from the first syllable of its paired word. On the rhyming task, we asked the same question with reference to word pairs’ final syllables. The mean correct answers across the two-tasks served as the total phonological awareness score.

out_desc_tool: A computerised assessment, the New Group Reading Test Digital (NGRT  GL Assessment, 2010) was used at all time points except t4. The test took approximately 45 min to complete and was supervised by one of the TAs in school. This is an adaptive, multiple-choice test that begins with a sentence completion task and then, depending upon the accuracy of responses, either drops down in difficulty to phonics tasks or becomes harder and assesses passage comprehension. The comprehension questions target a range of skills including inferencing and vocabulary. Given the adaptive nature of the test, pupils complete different subtests. Note  Reading Ability Scores (not standard scores) are reported, hence outcome is listed as a secondary measure.
out_es_type_tool: ['Post-test adjusted for baseline attainment AND clustering']

Essentially the listed words must be decoded and pronounced in a manner consistent with the articulation guidelines in order to be counted as correct. out_desc_red: The Diagnostic Reading Scales (DRS) (Spache, 1981) is a non­ standardized assessment tool that determines the level at which a child can read fluently and answer comprehension questions. The child is required to read a list of words. The examiner records the correct words and determines the grade placement from the raw score. The child is then requested to read a story at that grade level. Pass rate consists of less than 40% errors on oral reading and comprehension questions.

The children were asked to read aloud a series of short passages that were graded in difﬁculty. After completing each passage the child was presented with a series of questions relating to the passage. The reading comprehension score was based on the total number of correct responses to these questions.

out_desc_tool: Reading was assessed using the Phonemic Decoding Efﬁciency (PDE) form of Test of Word Reading Efﬁciency, featuring nonwords. Children were required to read as many non-words as they can in 45 s. The test yields a standard score mean of 100 and SD of 15. The raw score comprises the absolute number of words read in 45 s.
out_desc_red: Reading was assessed using the Sight Word Efﬁciency (SWE) form of Test of Word Reading Efﬁciency, featuring words. Children were required to read as many words as they can in 45 s.
